   =20
 =20

If you want to take over a US public company, the normal way to do it is by=
 calling up the company=E2=80=99s chief executive officer and proposing a m=
erger. You talk to the CEO, you work out a deal, the board approves, they s=
ubmit it to a shareholder vote, the shareholders approve, and then you buy =
all of the company=E2=80=99s stock for the price you agreed on.
A less common approach is the hostile tender offer: You call up the CEO, yo=
u propose a merger,=C2=A0she says =E2=80=9Cabsolutely not,=E2=80=9D you dec=
ide to do it anyway, so you make a public offer to the company=E2=80=99s sh=
areholders to buy all their stock at some fixed price. If a majority of the=
 shareholders tender their shares to you, then you control the company and =
get to replace the board and do more or less what you want.
  [1]

The weirdest approach would be to just go to the stock exchange and keep bu=
ying stock until you own a majority of the shares, and then say =E2=80=9CSu=
rprise! I own the company now.=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m sure someone has done t=
his before, but it is very much not normal practice. For one thing, it=E2=
=80=99s not like every share is=C2=A0available=C2=A0on the stock exchange: =
