If you are a bank with a private banking business for wealthy clients, the =
two main things that you want from your private bankers are:
=09You want them to serve their clients=E2=80=99 needs, put the clients fir=
st and=C2=A0make the=C2=A0clients feel well taken care of,=C2=A0so the clie=
nts stick with your bank, add more assets to the relationship, and recommen=
d your services to their friends.=09You want them to extract more=C2=A0reve=
nue=C2=A0from the clients, by upselling and cross-selling them on new produ=
cts that earn money for your bank.

Are these goals in conflict with each other? Oh, sure, absolutely, a lot of=
 the time: Often the best way to take care of clients is=C2=A0not=C2=A0by p=
utting them into a lot of high-fee products that are good for the bank. But=
 there really is a lot of overlap. Often the clients=C2=A0do=C2=A0want a lo=
an, or a fancy private investment vehicle, and setting them up with one is =
both good client service and good revenue generation. A good private banker=
 will do both things seamlessly; the clients will happily pay the bank lots=
 of money, because they feel like they=E2=80=99re getting good value.
If you are a really=C2=A0big=C2=A0bank with a private banking business, you=
 will hire hundreds of private bankers and let them loose on thousands of c=
lients and=C2=A0tell=C2=A0them to do those things, but you will have a hard=
 time measuring them. Good customer service can be approximated with anecdo=
tal feedback, surveys, data on churn, etc., but you won=E2=80=99t have perf=
ect visibility into how good each banker is at customer service. Revenue is=
 easier to measure, but also somewhat random =E2=80=94=C2=A0some bankers wi=
ll have clients who inherit fortunes and need more products, through no eff=
ort of the banker =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s harder to measure who is =
good at=C2=A0trying=C2=A0to generate revenue.=C2=A0
And so you might implement some  incredibly crude metric to decide which ba=
nkers are doing a good job of serving customers and pitching products:

Citigroup has started tracking how many calls its private bankers are makin=
