       =20
  [1] I am simplifying in many respects in these two paragraphs. You can ne=
gotiate a friendly tender offer (generally followed by a back-end merger). =
You can do a hostile merger (generally with a proxy fight). You can combine=
 these approaches: Threaten a hostile tender and use that threat to negotia=
te a quasi-friendly merger. If you get a majority of shares in the tender o=
ffer but *don=E2=80=99t* do a back-end merger, you have obligations to the =
minority shareholders and can=E2=80=99t do *whatever* you want with it. And=
 of course the board can try to block your hostile tender with a   poison p=
ill.=20


  [2] Some of these shares came from buying and exercising call options on =
the same day, why not.


  [3] PLCE is The Children=E2=80=99s Place=E2=80=99s ticker symbol.


  [4] Until we are all enslaved by robots I guess. But there=E2=80=99s a =
=E2=80=9Cwrong way=E2=80=9D that is like =E2=80=9Calmost all humans are red=
uced to working for the people who own the superintelligent robots,=E2=80=
=9D rather than =E2=80=9Call humans are reduced to working for the robots d=
irectly.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s a bad way to build AGI that still creates=
 human winners.


  [5] Well: =E2=80=9CThe board remains majority independent. Independent di=
rectors do not hold equity in OpenAI. Even OpenAI=E2=80=99s CEO, Sam Altman=
, does not hold equity directly. His only interest is indirectly through a =
Y Combinator investment fund that made a small investment in OpenAI before =
he was full-time.=E2=80=9D


  [6] The investors who want their money back, and the investors who want y=
ou to deploy their money, may or may not be different investors.=20


