<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want to take over a US public company, =
the normal way to do it is by calling up the company=E2=80=99s chief execut=
ive officer and proposing a merger. You talk to the CEO, you work out a dea=
l, the board approves, they submit it to a shareholder vote, the shareholde=
rs approve, and then you buy all of the company=E2=80=99s stock for the pri=
ce you agreed on.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A less common approach is the hostile tender o=
ffer: You call up the CEO, you propose a merger,=C2=A0she says =E2=80=9Cabs=
olutely not,=E2=80=9D you decide to do it anyway, so you make a public offe=
r to the company=E2=80=99s shareholders to buy all their stock at some fixe=
d price. If a majority of the shareholders tender their shares to you, then=
 you control the company and get to replace the board and do more or less w=
hat you want.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weirdest approach would be to just go to t=
he stock exchange and keep buying stock until you own a majority of the sha=
res, and then say =E2=80=9CSurprise! I own the company now.=E2=80=9D I=E2=
=80=99m sure someone has done this before, but it is very much not normal p=
ractice. For one thing, it=E2=80=99s not like every share is=C2=A0<em>avail=
able=C2=A0</em>on the stock exchange: Lots of stock will be owned by inside=
rs, index funds, loyal investors, etc., who have no interest in selling; if=
 more than 50% of the stock is owned by those sorts of long-term holders, y=
ou=E2=80=99ll never be able to buy it on the exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, even if you can get above 50%, it=E2=80=
=99ll take forever: Most stocks=E2=80=99 daily trading volume is a small fr=
action of the shares outstanding, so even if you buy=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em=
>of the shares each day, it will take you days to get a majority. And if yo=
u are buying all the shares, you are going to be pushing the price up, maki=
ng all of this uneconomical. Also, if you do this over several days,=C2=A0y=
ou will have to disclose your giant stake =E2=80=94=C2=A0and perhaps <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDYvZWxvbi1tdXN=
rLWlzLWFjdGl2ZS1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9bd9fd32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  your intentions</a=
> =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then people will know that you=E2=80=99re buying and w=
ill demand even higher prices.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, just, I mean, you=E2=80=99re buying a wh=
ole company? Don=E2=80=99t you want to=C2=A0<em>talk=C2=A0</em>to the CEO f=
irst? It=E2=80=99s possible that you=E2=80=99ll call the CEO and she=E2=80=
=99ll say =E2=80=9Cget lost, we=E2=80=99re fine here without you,=E2=80=9D =
and you=E2=80=99ll disagree and decide to buy up the stock anyway and fire =
her, but don=E2=80=99t you at least want to know that first? The friendly m=
erger and the hostile tender offer are traditional ways to start a process =
that ends with you in charge of the company, and they are ways for you to u=
nderstand what you are getting into. Just buying stock on the exchange unti=
l you stumble=C2=A0into control of the company is weird.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nevertheless,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VtYWZvci5jb=
20vbmV3c2xldHRlci8wMi8xNS8yMDI0L2Etd2VhbHRoeS1zYXVkaS1mYW1pbHktaXMtYnV5aW5n=
LXVwLWZhaWxpbmctY2hpbGRyZW5zLXBsYWNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77b7f683" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> Semafor=E2=80=99s Liz Hoffman reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since The Children=E2=80=99s Place =E2=80=94 o=
nce a defining feature of American malls =E2=80=94 said last week that it w=
as running out of cash, more than half of its stock has been snapped up by =
the Al-Rajhi family, the founders of Saudi Arabia=E2=80=99s largest private=
 bank.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mithaq Capital, which invests some of the Al-R=
ajhi family fortune, bought 46% of the retailer=E2=80=99s shares on Friday =
and Monday, and another 8% on Tuesday, corporate filings show, and plans to=
 replace the board. Semafor reported the hostile approach Wednesday.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All in, Mithaq spent at least $80 million to b=
uy control of a public company in three trading sessions =E2=80=94 an unhea=
rd-of blitz for even the most aggressive of hostile bidders and corporate a=
gitators.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a Mithaq=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDIyNTUxL3hzbEYzNDVYM=
DIvdG0yNDYxODItMV8zc2VxMS54bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB065d1d21" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
filing</a>=C2=A0reporting that, on Friday, it acquired more than 10% of the=
 stock and was thus required to file ownership reports.=C2=A0Here is anothe=
r <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY=
1OTI0MDIyNTUyL3hzbEYzNDVYMDUvdG0yNDYxODItMl80c2VxMS54bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB1b66ddfd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> filing</a>=C2=A0reporting that it bought another =
1.8 million shares later on Friday, taking it up to 3.1 million shares, or =
about a quarter of the company. Here is another <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bc=
mNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDI0MTgxL3hzbEYzNDVYMDUv=
dG0yNDYzMzYtMV80c2VxMS54bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB534f00b9" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> fil=
ing</a>=C2=A0reporting that it bought a further 2.7 million shares on Monda=
y, bringing it up to 46%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And apparently it got to 54% on Tuesday, because here=E2=80=99s a=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0vQXJjaGl2ZXMvZWRnYXI=
vZGF0YS8xMDQxODU5LzAwMDA5NTAxNDIyNDAwMDQ1NC9laDI0MDQ0OTAwNV84ay5odG0/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBa387e139" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> announcement from the company</a>:</p=
>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On February 14, 2024, The Children=
=E2=80=99s Place, Inc. (the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) received corresponde=
nce from Mithaq Capital SPC (=E2=80=9CMithaq=E2=80=9D) notifying the Compan=
y that they own approximately 54% of the Company=E2=80=99s outstanding shar=
es of common stock. The Company had previously received notice from Mithaq =
and its related parties of their intent to nominate 11 director candidates =
to stand for election to the Company=E2=80=99s Board of Directors at the Co=
mpany=E2=80=99s 2024 Annual Meeting of Shareholders. The Company intends to=
 accept Mithaq=E2=80=99s request to enter into discussions regarding the pr=
ovision of financing to assist with the Company=E2=80=99s liquidity needs.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mithaq=C2=A0just =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bought the com=
pany in the open market over the course of three days? Wild stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What=E2=80=99s even better is that Mithaq=E2=
=80=99s purchase price was at a deep=C2=A0<em>discount </em>to the stock=E2=
=80=99s trading price before it started buying. The Children=E2=80=99s Plac=
e=E2=80=99s stock closed at $19.75 last Thursday; Mithaq bought all of its =
shares for $17.10 or less. To be fair, there were reasons for this; <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cueWV0YW5vdGhlcnZhbHVlYmxvZy5jb20vcC90aGUtY3VyaW91cy1jYXNlLW9mLXBsY2Ut=
YW5kLXRoZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8140427d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
