ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 reported=C2=A0today</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">OpenAI Startup Fund was launched in late 2021 =
to invest in other AI startups and projects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By last May it reported $175 million in total =
commitments, and a portfolio that included video editor Descript and legal =
tool Harvey.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It always had outside limited partners, includ=
ing major OpenAI partner Microsoft, which is unusual for corporate VC funds=
 but not unique.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What set OpenAI Startup Fund apart, however, w=
as that it wasn't (and isn't) owned by OpenAI. Nor even by its affiliated n=
onprofit foundation. Instead, it's legally owned by Altman. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=C2=A0"We wanted to get started quickly and th=
e easiest way to do that due to our structure was to put it in Sam's name,"=
 an OpenAI spokesperson tells Axios. "We have always intended for this to b=
e temporary."</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"Temporary" has been well over a year and it's=
 a significant risk. For example, what might have happened had Altman remai=
ned fired by OpenAI. Could he have kept the fund? Was there anything contra=
ctual to prevent it?</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Maybe? It=E2=80=99s fine? Sam Altman runs one =
of the biggest and hottest startups in the world, but he doesn=E2=80=99t ow=
n any of its stock, because of its unique concern with purity. But he wants=
 to get paid like he runs one of the biggest and hottest startups in the wo=
rld. So why shouldn=E2=80=99t he get to own some of its ancillary spinoff p=
rojects? He can get rich off the video editor and the legal tool, and Micro=
soft can get rich off ChatGPT, and SoftBank can get rich investing in chipm=
akers, and everyone can get rich off of something as long as no one gets ri=
ch off of AGI. That has to be kept pure, for humanity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know, this is all a little abs=
urd, but if you take the first premise seriously =E2=80=94=C2=A0that OpenAI=
 wants to build AGI, and that building AGI the correct way is existentially=
 important for humanity =E2=80=94=C2=A0then it sort of makes sense. It woul=
d normally be conventional wisdom to say that it=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0<em>confl=
ict of interest=C2=A0</em>for the CEO of a big company to own its venture a=
rm personally: What if he takes a corporate opportunity that ought to belon=
g to the company? But OpenAI is not, fundamentally, in the business of busi=
ness; it=E2=80=99s not in the business of seizing commercial opportunities =
to make money for its shareholders. Oh sure it=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>that=
, but only as a tool to achieve its real goal, of making AGI. Letting its c=
elebrity CEO profit from the venture arm, but not from the main product, so=
mehow=C2=A0<em>aligns=C2=A0</em>everyone=E2=80=99s interests.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course the actual conflict of interest=C2=
=A0is, what if one of the venture investments builds AGI first? In the bad =
way? What if Sam Altman looks around and is like =E2=80=9Cman, someone coul=
d get rich building AGI, but I can=E2=80=99t get rich if I build it at Open=
AI due to its purity, so I=E2=80=99d better fund someone else who=E2=80=99l=
l do it in the commercial way=E2=80=9D?</p>
