<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weird story in private equity these days i=
s that private equity firms have two, as far as I can tell,=C2=A0exactly of=
fsetting problems:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They have investors who have given th=
em a lot of money recently and want them to spend it buying companies.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They have investors who gave them a lo=
t of money years ago, which they used to buy companies, and now those inves=
tors would like them to sell those companies and give them the money back.<=
/li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the Financial Times <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL=
2NvbnRlbnQvMDc5Y2NkZTYtM2MzZC00NzkxLTk1M2ItNmUzZTgyMDNlZjEy/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB58acae62" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> put it last month</a>, they have =E2=80=9Cre=
cord amounts of unspent investor cash and an unprecedented stockpile of age=
ing deals that firms must sell in coming years.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMDIvZmFrZS1zdXJnZXJpZX=
MtYXJlLXNlY3VyaXRpZXMtZnJhdWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZ=
Gl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1w=
YWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf70e69a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I wrote</a>=
:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CDoesn=E2=80=99t it seem like this should be a solvable prob=
lem?=E2=80=9D What you do is, you take the money that the investors want yo=
u to spend on buying companies, and you use it to buy the companies that th=
e investors want you to sell, so you can give the money back to those inves=
tors.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously there are details to work out, but i=
f every private equity firm is in this situation, I have confidence that th=
ey can work out those details. I use my new fund to buy a company you own i=
n your old fund, you use your new fund to buy a company that I own in my ol=
d fund, everybody=E2=80=99s happy. This just does not seem like the most ch=
allenging problem of financial engineering that the private equity industry=
 has ever faced.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here are KKR and Veritas, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
ud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9ra3ItdG8tYWNxdWlyZS1hLXN0YWtlLWluLWNvdGl2aXRpLWZyb2=
0tdmVyaXRhcy1jYXBpdGFsLWRkZmY1NjUxP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB162e9667" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> handling it</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">KKR &amp; Co. has agreed to acquire a stake in=
 Cotiviti from private-equity manager Veritas Capital in a deal valuing the=
 healthcare-technology business at around $11 billion.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The transaction would give the two New York-ba=
sed firms equal ownership stakes in Cotiviti, according to an announcement =
planned for Wednesday. The Wall Street Journal reported in December that th=
e firms were in discussions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal would rank among the largest recent p=
rivate-equity transactions. Buyout firms slowed dealmaking after the Federa=
l Reserve began raising interest rates in 2022, with the debt used to finan=
ce acquisitions getting more expensive and harder to obtain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal would also represent a significant pa=
yday for Veritas, which took Cotiviti private for about $4.16 billion in 20=
18. The firm specializes in buyouts of companies at the intersection of tec=
hnology and government. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Veritas plans to invest new capital in Cotivit=
i alongside KKR=E2=80=99s commitment to help fund the company=E2=80=99s gro=
wth. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">KKR=E2=80=99s investment in Cotiviti comes fro=
m KKR North America Fund XIII, a $19 billion vehicle closed in 2022, and Ve=
ritas=E2=80=99s new investment comes from Veritas Fund VIII, a $10.65 billi=
on pool that closed the same year.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right, if you bought a company in your old fun=
d in 2018, it=E2=80=99s time to cash that fund out. So you invest in that c=
ompany from your new fund, which (1) helps you deploy that new fund (which =
the new fund=E2=80=99s investors want) and (2) helps you cash out the old f=
und (which the old fund=E2=80=99s investors want). There are <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34364292.279392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTgvYnV5b3V0LWZ1bmRzLWJ=
1eS1mcm9tLXRoZW1zZWx2ZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjE1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8a18f43f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  questions abou=
t valuation</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t want to overpay (hurting t=
he new fund) or underpay (hurting the old fund) =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you g=
et an outside investor (KKR) that kind of answers those questions; presumab=
ly KKR negotiated a market price. And of course KKR needs to deploy its new=
 fund too. Plus opening up the market for big secondary deals probably help=
s KKR if it too needs to cash out its old funds.</p>
